english:
  title: A Poem Sequence Presented to Kim Ui-gyeong, Vice Director of the Collation Bureau
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A scholar born into this world—how constant are his comings and goings? When summoned to great service, he walks a great path. When called to lesser tasks, he treads a lesser way. And when not called at all, he moves not. Thus it is, nothing more. Yet only those who truly possess within themselves a clear understanding of inner and outer, of the weights and measures of the world, can accomplish this. My friend Kim Ui-gyeong studied the ancients to become a scholar, waiting for his time to come. In the year of Gyesa, when the venerable Masters Li Yun-jae and Hong Yang-pa, with their established virtue and weighty reputation, held the seat of authority and wielded the power to choose among men, those scholars who harbored brilliant schemes and deep insight, hidden away and unnoticed, all stirred to life. They sang and leaped forth, saying, "Now is the hour!" Shoulder to shoulder they pressed forward into the halls of examination, each vying to prove his worth. And so Ui-gyeong, conversing freely with Master Han-san of Mok-eun, rose and moved boldly ahead while his peers stood back in awe, knowing they could not match him. He surpassed the multitude and stood foremost, achieving high honors in the third rank—how remarkable! For his reputation in letters and learning, he entered the Bureau of Collation, taking charge of textual verification. Soon after, noted for his sincerity and forthright integrity, he was appointed Left Remonstrator and Keeper of the Household Records, permitted to speak freely on the gains and losses of governance, and even to judge the fitness of appointments. He seemed near to great employment. Yet Ui-gyeong's talents and learning deserved something greater, for the true measure of his gifts remained untested. One day, his father growing old, he withdrew and returned south, standing at his bedside morning and night, departing not from his side. So he harbored no desire for office, nor any desire to advance.

    Now the Minister of State, the noble Master Ha, having assumed command of the Jeolla Region, declared upon arrival: "The burden of provincial stewardship is heavy, the duties of army and people are manifold. The laws of governance and strategies of warfare must be shaped through counsel with the worthy and wise." He summoned Ui-gyeong to his inner council, treating him as an honored guest. Ui-gyeong, moved by such recognition, held nothing back in speech, spared no stratagem in counsel. The armies' commands rang clear, the province's taxes and disputes were justly settled. The military achieved victory, and the people knew peace. Ui-gyeong said, "This success comes because my lord is virtuous." The Minister replied, "Not so—it is the counsel of my guest that brings it to pass." Thus was his merit reported, and he received the rank of Honored Counselor, Vice Director of the Collation Bureau, and Direct Academician of the Precious Literature Pavilion, marking his service with honor. Ui-gyeong's talents, applied in the Minister's court, now flourished in the provincial administration, and his lord's achievements stood secure. Where can such ability not succeed?

    In days of old, during Tang, there were Masters Lu Mai, Zheng Yuqing, Zhao Zongru, and Gu Xiaolian, who served as provincial counselors and later rose to the rank of Chancellor. Men of their time honored them, and their fair renown echoes still. It is said that "a Chancellor serves the throne through the advancement of men." When our Minister one day returns to court and brings forward hidden talents, promoting the worthy and excellent, surely Ui-gyeong's name shall stand foremost. How could we allow Tang's provincial counselors alone to hold all the glory? Though I am cast aside and forgotten, I have not yet departed this life. I shall wipe my eyes and wait to see Ui-gyeong rise to great service and walk his great path.
  footnotes:
    - Li Yun-jae (李益齋) and Hong Yang-pa (洪陽坡) were influential Neo-Confucian scholars and officials of the early Joseon period who oversaw the civil service examinations.
    - The 'three ranks' (丙科) represents the third tier of successful candidates in the civil service examination system.
    - The reference to Tang Dynasty officials serving as provincial counselors before becoming chancellors reflects the historical example that the author believes Ui-gyeong should emulate.
    - The work was written by Jeong Do-jeon (1342-1398), a founding figure of the Joseon Dynasty and chief architect of its political system.
